[normal]Written evidence submitted by [bold]Dr Neil T. Gavin[bold], [bold]The University of Liverpool[bold] (CLC026)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]1.
[normal]              
[normal]Executive summary[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]1.1
[normal]              
[normal]Current research gives us limited understanding of 
[normal]how 
[normal]the structure and content of 
[normal]media 
[normal]coverage impinges on public understanding of climate change.
[normal] 
[normal]W
[normal]ork done 
[normal]o
[normal]n television
[normal] coverage – the public’s most trusted and most used source of information – has 
[normal]been undertaken
[normal] by 
[normal]this submission’s 
[normal]author
[normal]. I
[normal]t illuminates a set of worrying patterns that are under-explored by principal funders of research.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.2
[normal]              
[normal]Unique research undertaken by the author suggests televisual coverage 
[normal]of climate change has diminished. But such coverage as there is 
[normal]has a measurable influence on the emphasis that citizens place on the topic as a significant issue facing Britain. This 
[normal]‘salience’ 
[normal]is an important precursor to further public engagement, but needs to be viewed in the light of climate sceptic
[normal] coverage
[normal] (a topic also under-explored in research)
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3
[normal]              
[normal]This
[normal] submission suggests that the main research funders need encourage
[normal]ment
[normal] to support 
[normal]work that 
[normal]integrat
[normal]es
[normal] of research on public attitude formation
[normal] (heavily funded)
[normal], with long-term assessments o
[normal]f press and television coverage of climate change.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.4
[normal]              
[normal]Broadcasters in both the non-commercial and commercial sectors need to be challenged on the emphasis place
[normal]d
[normal] on documenting climate change. In addition, senior government 
[normal]politicians 
[normal]ought to be challenged on the extent to which they are prepared to invest political capital in raising the profile of climate change. Finally, 
[normal]press 
[normal]editors should be challenged on the
[normal]ir
[normal] rationale 
[normal]for 
[normal]continued emphasis on climate sceptic
[normal]ism
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.
[normal]              
[normal]Introduction[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]2.
[normal]1
[normal]              
[normal]This evidence is 
[normal]based on 
[normal]the author’s extensive contribution to 
[normal]political communication 
[normal]research. Th
[normal]is straddles 
[normal]climate-related public relations, the coverage of climate change in all significant media (press, television and the internet),
[normal]1
[normal] and the media’s impact on public attitu
[normal]d
[normal]es.
[normal]2
[normal] The author of this 
[normal]is 
[normal]also currently Convenor of the Media, Communication and Cultural Studies Association’s ‘Climate Change, Environment and Sustainability network, an umbrella organisation for scholars research
[normal]ing
[normal] environmental issues.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2
[normal]              
[normal]The evidence is also given against 
[normal]a 
[normal]background of ongoing 
[normal]exploratory 
[normal]research on climate change coverage
[normal]’s impact
[normal] on public attitudes, 
[normal]and 
[normal]the incidence of climate sceptic coverage in the 
[normal]British 
[normal]press.
