[normal]Factual Information[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]Background
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1
[normal]              
[normal]T
[normal]he press is currently taking a diminishing interest in climate (
[normal]see 
[normal]Figure 3.1).
[normal] This is worryingly consistent with the rise, plateau and decline pattern outlined in ‘issue attention cycle’ thesis, with we may well be at a phase characterised by declining interest and a ‘post-problem’ mentality.
[normal]4
[normal] Here, spikes around the Copenhagen conference and recently, are not necessarily reassuring, as they may represent the ‘spasmodic recurrence’ of attention allowed for in this perspective. In addition, this overarching pattern cannot be looked at in isolation from the much, much larger quantity of coverage that bears on non-climate, ‘bread-and-butter’ issues, like crime, health and economics.
[normal]1
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]Figure 3.1
[normal] UK Press Stories Containing ‘Climate’
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Source: 
[normal]http://sciencepolicy.colorado.edu/media_coverage/uk/index.html
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]3.2
[normal]              
[normal]The 
[normal]underlying structure 
[normal]of this coverage 
[normal]has some features that are 
[normal]well established
[normal]. First, the broadsheet 
[normal](and notably 
[normal]the Guardian and Independent
[normal])
[normal] make a
[normal] very
[normal] notable contribution. Second, 
[normal]broadsheet 
[normal]coverage has a sophisticated take on climate change, with sceptical messages
[normal], according to some assessments,
[normal] much less apparent than they were.
[normal]5
[normal] 
[normal]Third, 
[normal]the high circulation mid-market and tabloid press takes a lesser interest
[normal], but 
[normal]th
[normal]e tabloid
[normal] 
[normal]in particular are 
[normal]not trusted, nor 
[normal]are they 
[normal]cited 
[normal]by citizens 
[normal]as their principal 
[normal]information 
[normal]source
[normal]. 
[normal]Nevertheless, the 
[normal]wider 
[normal]literature 
[normal]on ‘media effects’ 
[normal]suggests that 
[normal]broadsheet
[normal]s
[normal] and 
[normal]the mid-market ‘
[normal]black top
[normal]’
[normal] 
[normal]titles 
[normal]ha
[normal]ve
[normal] the 
[normal]potential
[normal] to influence public appreciat
[normal]ion of 
[normal]climate change.
[normal]2
[normal] 
[normal]Other 
[normal]work 
[normal]on public perceptions of the climate commentary 
[normal]suggests the 
[normal]citizens 
[normal]cite the media as a source of climate information, talk to family and friends about 
[normal]such 
[normal]coverage, but nevertheless continue to dispute 
[normal]global warming’s 
[normal]anthropogenic basis, and are still confused about the science.
[normal]6
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.
[normal]3
[normal]              
[normal]What is much 
[normal]less
[normal] well-understood, is how 
[normal]television 
[normal]which 
[normal]is
[normal] trusted use
[normal]d
[normal] as a 
[normal]reliable information
[normal], refract
[normal]s
[normal] climate issues. The author’s research suggest that even at significant ‘moments’ for climate change (such as Copenhagen, 2009), television 
[normal]news
[normal] coverage 
[normal]is 
[normal]quite modest, a 
[normal]historical 
[normal]pattern 
[normal]noted by others
[normal].
[normal]7
[normal] 
[normal]It 
[normal]also suggest
[normal]ed
[normal] that climate sceptic messages 
[normal]are 
[normal]more prominent than 
[normal]is commonly acknowledged, or 
[normal]healthy. 
[normal]However
[normal], there is very little research that deals 
[normal]directly
[normal] with the impact of 
[normal]such 
[normal]coverage.
[normal]6
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.4
[normal]              
[normal]Some c
[normal]urrent research has sought to 
[normal]update what the public think about climate change, and how this relate
[normal]s
[normal] to media representations
[normal], sponsored by UKERC and by a combination of NERC, DECC and Defra
[normal].
[normal]8
[normal] However, solid as 
[normal]this work is
[normal], 
[normal]it suffers 
[normal]in 
[normal]some 
[normal]important respect
[normal]s. 
[normal]The focus is primarily on attitudes and attitude development. But 
[normal]it 
[normal]is not 
[normal]closely 
[normal]articulat
[normal]ed
[normal] to 
[normal]an assessment of the 
[normal]long-term 
[normal]patterning of 
[normal]coverage
[normal] across 
[normal]all
[normal] media
[normal] (especially
[normal], though not exclusively,
[normal] with regard to 
[normal]TV coverage
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]or 
[normal]the prevalence of climate sceptic messages
[normal] across 
[normal]the 
[normal]media
[normal]).
[normal] 
[normal]Finally, 
[normal]with a reliance on focus group
[normal] techniques
[normal] 
[normal]it 
[normal]does not 
[normal]explore the 
[normal]full range of ways in which ‘media impact’ is 
[normal]generally 
[normal]conceived and evidenced.
