[normal]3.6
[normal]              
[normal]The 
[normal]structure 
[normal]of documentary coverage 
[normal]is 
[normal]concerning
[normal] for a number of reasons. 
[normal]First, the vast bulk of these documentaries are
[normal] on BBC,
[normal] 
[normal]not
[normal] 
[normal]the 
[normal]commercial
[normal] channels
[normal]. This 
[normal]is 
[normal]understandable, if commercial broadcasters consider this form of programming 
[normal]un
[normal]likely to draw 
[normal]large 
[normal]audience, and hence 
[normal]generate 
[normal]limited 
[normal]advertising revenue. 
[normal]But this 
[normal]perhaps 
[normal]consign
[normal]s
[normal] 
[normal]their duty to keep the public informed about one of the most commanding issues of our generation, 
[normal]to a 
[normal]second-order 
[normal]priority
[normal]. 
[normal]Second
[normal], of the last three documentaries, only one 
[normal]was 
[normal]on 
[normal]BBC1
[normal]. Before th
[normal]is
[normal], 
[normal]there was only 
[normal]one in late 2009 and 
[normal]another in 
[normal]mid-2010
[normal]. T
[normal]he rest 
[normal]predate March 2007.
[normal]This 
[normal]too 
[normal]is significant. 
[normal]BBC1 is 
[normal]the 
[normal]place where viewers 
[normal]are most likely to 
[normal]encounter documentar
[normal]ies
[normal]. They
[normal] watch
[normal] 
[normal]around 
[normal]9.8 hours per year on 
[normal]BBC1
[normal],
[normal]8
[normal] 
[normal]s
[normal]o a drop of
[normal]f
[normal] here is potentially significant
[normal] for audience exposure to the issue
[normal]. ITV1 is next in line
[normal], with the
[normal] public watching 
[normal]3.8
[normal] hours per year
[normal] on this channel
[normal] – a considerable way behind
[normal]. 
[normal]But a
[normal]lthough the last two 
