[normal] – unlike 
[normal]all 
[normal]others 
[normal]– 
[normal]its 
[normal]highly controversial 
[normal]message was unequivocally 
[normal]at odds with the scientific consensus
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.8
[normal]              
[normal]The results suggest that only broadsheet coverage had an impact on 
[normal]‘
[normal]salience
[normal]’
[normal].
[normal] There was no such impact for 
[normal]either 
[normal]the ‘black tops’ or ‘red tops’, nor did the political event variables achieve statistical significance
[normal]. But importantly there was an interaction effect between broadsheet coverage and documentary coverage
[normal]: 
[normal]in effect, the two mediums 
[normal]conjoin
[normal] to produce a greater influence on salience, than the broadsheet press would on its own. 
[normal]A
[normal]ddition
[normal]ally
[normal], the ‘Great Global Warming Swindle’ had a
[normal]n independent,
[normal] measurable and statistically significant impact 
[normal]in 
[normal]lowering
[normal] salience
[normal]. This
[normal] 
[normal]particular 
[normal]finding 
[normal]is un
[normal]surprising 
[normal]in 
[normal]some 
[normal]respect
[normal]s
[normal]. ‘Swindle
[normal]’s highly controversial nature helped generate an audience of near
[normal]ly
[normal] two million, in all likelihood far beyond that of many (if not all) the other documentaries
[normal]. In addition, it generated supportive commentary in the Telegraph and 
[normal]the 
[normal]black top press
[normal].
[normal]1
[normal] But
[normal],
[normal] if 
[normal]un
[normal]surprising, 
[normal]the finding 
[normal]is 
[normal]still 
[normal]worrying, given its 
[normal]potent 
[normal]counter-consensus message.
[normal] The results underscore the problematic nature of Channel 4’s defence of its broadcast, on the grounds that it 
[normal]balanced
[normal] a portfolio of environmental output which also contained material 
[normal]consistent 
[normal]with the scientific consensus.
[normal]9
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.9
[normal]              
[normal]Given the findings, it is no surprise that with climate change now diminished in press coverage (Figure 3.1), and documentary coverage dwindling (Figure 4.1), the salience of the environment is at a record and worrying low, and on a sharp downward track.
[normal] 10
[normal] 
[normal]But another feature of ongoing research 
[normal]on the British press 
[normal]is pertinent here. It 
[normal]has t
[normal]r
[normal]acked climate sceptic messages in our national newspapers, and 
[normal]suggests unchallenged 
[normal]contrarian 
[normal]commentary is still persistent in 
[normal]a 
[normal]broadsheet 
[normal]press that helps drive the salience of climate (notably in the Telegraph), and in 
[normal]a 
[normal]black top press that so conspicuously supported the ‘Great Global Warming Swindle’ documentary.
[normal]3
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.0
[normal]              
[normal]Conclusions[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]4
[normal].
[normal]1
[normal]              
[normal]From 
[normal]th
[normal]e 
[normal]perspective
[normal] of the evidence presented here
[normal], the picture is concern
[normal]ing
[normal]. It invites us to consider 
[normal]a number of 
[normal]interrelated 
[normal]issues. 
[normal]To what extent do we need a research agenda that takes into consideration the structure of climate change coverage in the widest possible range of media? Do we need to find a way to integrate existing research on climate attitudes and attitude development, with a fuller appreciation of these structures. And to what extent do the principal funders of such research need to 
[normal]be encouraged to 
[normal]acknowledge 
[normal]such 
[normal]issues?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2
[normal]              
[normal]In addition, there are questions for the broadcasters
[normal] and for the press
[normal]. Given the remit 
[normal]of the former 
[normal]to educate and inform the public, h
[normal]ow 
[normal]far 
[normal]are they prepared to 
[normal]go to 
[normal]document 
[normal]climate 
[normal]change 
[normal]in the future?
[normal] 
[normal]W
[normal]ill 
[normal]th
[normal]eir
[normal] output reflect the urgency the scientific com
[normal]munity express about the issue
[normal], and will this be tempered significantly by concerns about audience figures and advertising revenue
[normal]? 
[normal]And t
[normal]o what extent will 
[normal]counter-consensus messages like that embodied in the ‘Great Global Warming Swindle’
[normal] be given a place in broadcasting output?
[normal] For 
[normal]newspaper 
[normal]editors, some of the same themes emerge. Although, the press acknowledge no obligation to inform or educate the public, they should perhaps consider more fully than they do at present, the potential impact their coverage has, and the extent to which it serves the public good.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3
[normal]              
[normal]Finally, what role do senior government politicians have in heightening the media profile of climate change? 
[normal]The media often take their cue on what is important from these figures. 
[normal]Here
[normal],
[normal] the issue of political leadership 
[normal]comes 
[normal]to the forefront.
